This is an advanced issue for an experienced Zulip developer.

When we come out of a suspended state in the browser, it can take a few seconds before we re-connect to the server's event system.  When that happens, we should explicitly note that state so that the app can query something like `events_healthy()` to make sure we're currently processing events.

If events are not yet obviously healthy, some pieces of code should not run until we confirm that we're processing events again.  The best example of this is our activity query that gets presence info for all users.  If we are behind on events, we may have not yet processed a `realm_user/add` event, and that unknown-to-us-yet user will cause us to throw a blueslip error.  (We could suppress the blueslip error, of course, but then we're blind to other bugs.)

Once we implement a maybe-down state, we should have a function like `channel.post_when_healthy()` that can defer server requests until the event system is known to be healthy again.  Conceptually, it would work as follows:

~~~ js
exports.post_when_healthy = function (...) {
    if event_system_is_healthy() {
        exports.post(...);
    } else {
        requests.push(...);
    }   
};

exports.on_events_back_up = function (...) {
    _.each(requests, function (req) {
        exports.post(...);
    });
};
~~~

And then our first use of the above code would be in `activity.js` for the bulk presence updates.

